@startuml text-to-sql-flow
title Text-to-SQL Pipeline

skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true
skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam sequence {
    ArrowColor #444
    ActorBorderColor #444
    LifeLineBorderColor #888
    ParticipantBackgroundColor #EEF2FF
    ParticipantBorderColor #6366F1
    BoxBackgroundColor #F0F4FF
    BoxBorderColor #C7D2FE
    NoteBackgroundColor #FEF9C3
    NoteBorderColor #EAB308
}

actor       User          as U
participant "Frontend"    as FE  #EEF2FF
participant "FastAPI\nai-service" as API #EEF2FF
participant "Schema\nContext Layer"  as SCL #DBEAFE
participant "claude-opus-4-6"        as LLM #FCE7F3
database    "keycloak DB\n(remittance / payment)" as KDB #D1FAE5
database    "ml_db\n(ml_schema / service_mgmt)"   as MDB #D1FAE5
database    "ops_db\n(query_history)"              as ODB #E0E7FF
participant "Langfuse"    as LF  #FEF3C7

== Step 1: User asks a natural language question ==

U   ->  FE  : "How many transactions failed today\nbroken down by hub?"
FE  ->  API : POST /api/v1/assistant/query\n{ "question": "..." }
API ->  FE  : SSE stream open (text/event-stream)
API ->  LF  : trace.start("text_to_sql")\n{ input: { question } }

== Step 2: Build schema context ==

API ->  SCL : build_schema_context()
note right of SCL
  Whitelisted tables only:
  - remittance.transaction
  - service_management.remit_service
  - service_management.external_partner
  - ml_schema.country
  - ml_schema.ml_fx_rates

  PII columns stripped:
  sender_msisdn, sender_fullname,
  sender_dob, recipient_msisdn,
  recipient_fullname, recipient_dob

  Join hints:
  transaction.service_id
    → remit_service.remit_service_id
end note
SCL --> API : compact schema string\n+ status enum groups\n+ join hints

API --> FE  : {type:"status", text:"Generating SQL..."}

== Step 3: Claude generates SQL ==

API ->  LF  : span.start("generate_sql")
API ->  LLM : system prompt + schema context\n+ few-shot examples + user question
note right of LLM
  Few-shot examples in prompt:
  Q: "failures today by hub?"
  A: SELECT hub_name, COUNT(*) ...
     FROM remittance.transaction
     WHERE status LIKE '%FAILED%'
     AND created_date::date = CURRENT_DATE
     GROUP BY hub_name
end note
LLM --> API : generated SQL string
API ->  LF  : span.end("generate_sql") { sql }

API --> FE  : {type:"sql", sql:"SELECT hub_name, COUNT(*) ..."}

== Step 4: Validate SQL ==

API ->  LF  : span.start("validate_sql")
API ->  API : safety check — reject if\nINSERT / UPDATE / DELETE /\nDROP / CREATE / TRUNCATE
API ->  LF  : span.end("validate_sql") { valid }

alt SQL contains write operation
    API ->  LF  : trace.end — level ERROR
    API --> FE : {type:"error", code:"sql_validation_rejected",\nmessage:"I can only run read queries"}
    FE  --> U  : "I can only run read queries"
else SQL is SELECT-only
    API ->  LF  : span.start("explain_dry_run")
    API ->  KDB : EXPLAIN <generated SQL> (dry-run)
    note right of KDB
      EXPLAIN forces the DB planner to
      parse and validate the SQL without
      executing it — catches bad column
      names and syntax errors cheaply.
    end note
    API ->  LF  : span.end("explain_dry_run") { valid }
    alt EXPLAIN fails (bad column / syntax)
        KDB --> API : PlannerError
        API ->  LF  : trace.end — level ERROR
        API --> FE  : {type:"error", code:"sql_generation_failed",\nmessage:"Could not generate valid SQL"}
        FE  --> U   : error message
    end
end

== Step 5: Route to correct database engine ==

note over API
  DB Router:
  - remittance.* / customer.* / payment.*  → keycloak engine
  - ml_schema.* / service_management.*     → ml_db engine
  - cross-schema query                     → query both, join in Python
end note

API ->  LF  : span.start("execute_sql")
alt query targets keycloak schema
    API ->  KDB : execute SQL
    KDB --> API : result rows
else query targets ml_db schema
    API ->  MDB : execute SQL
    MDB --> API : result rows
else cross-DB query
    API ->  KDB : sub-query (keycloak tables)
    KDB --> API : partial rows
    API ->  MDB : sub-query (ml_db tables)
    MDB --> API : partial rows
    API ->  API : merge results in Python
end
API ->  LF  : span.end("execute_sql") { row_count, engine }

alt no rows returned
    API --> FE : {type:"error", code:"no_results",\nmessage:"No data found for that query"}
end

== Step 6: Claude explains the result ==

API ->  LF  : span.start("stream_explanation")
API ->  LLM : original question + result rows
note right of LLM
  "Given this data, explain in 2-4
  sentences what it means for the
  operations team. Be concise and
  actionable."
end note

LLM --> API : explanation tokens (streaming)
API --> FE  : {type:"token", text:"Today there were..."} x N
API --> FE  : [DONE]
API ->  LF  : span.end("stream_explanation") { explanation_chars }
API ->  LF  : trace.end { sql, engine, row_count }

== Step 7: Save to query history ==

API ->  ODB : INSERT query_history\n{ question, sql, timestamp }
note right of ODB
  Stored in ops_db (portal-owned).
  Deduplicates by question (keeps latest).
  Max 50 entries; favorites are preserved
  when history is cleared.
  Tags trace with APP_ENV (local / uat).
end note

== Rendered in Frontend ==

FE  --> U   : SQL block (collapsible) +\nexplanation text (streamed)\n+ History panel updated

@enduml
